Open AI

Whisper - Audio transcription pipeline
1. Doctor records consultation audio in the Streamlit UI. The audio file (mp3/wav) is uploaded directly to an AWS S3 bucket you configured.
2. S3 pre-signed URL is generated so the file can be securely passed to the OpenAI API without exposing your bucket publicly.
3. OpenAI Whisper API (whisper-1 model) receives the audio and returns a full text transcript. Whisper handles accents, medical terminology, and mixed-language speech better than most ASR systems.
4. Transcript is passed downstream to the LangChain RAG chain for clinical analysis.
response = openai.Audio.transcribe(
  model="whisper-1",
  file=audio_file
)
transcript = response["text"]

LangChain + GPT-4 - RAG chain for clinical reasoning
1. Transcript embedding — the incoming transcript is embedded using OpenAI's text-embedding-ada-002 model to generate a query vector.
2. Pinecone retrieval — the query vector is used to fetch the top-k most similar medication/symptom records from Pinecone (semantic search). These become the "context."
3. Prompt construction via LangChain — a RetrievalQA chain is built that injects the retrieved context alongside the transcript into a structured system prompt for GPT-4.
4. GPT-4 generates output — a structured clinical summary: symptoms identified, possible diagnoses, and medication/treatment recommendations grounded in the retrieved data.

chain = RetrievalQA.from_chain_type(
  llm=ChatOpenAI(model="gpt-4"),
  retriever=vectorstore.as_retriever(k=5),
  chain_type="stuff"
)
result = chain.run(transcript)

PineCone

Embeddings - What you built and why it matters
Pinecone stores high-dimensional vector representations of medication text so GPT-4 can retrieve relevant knowledge at inference time — instead of being limited to what it learned during training. I owned this entire embedding pipeline.
Step by step - How you built the index
1. Raw medication data came from Snowflake — structured records scraped from MedlinePlus by your teammate Shubh (drug names, indications, side effects, dosages).
2. Chunking — long text fields were split into smaller chunks (~300–500 tokens) so embeddings are semantically focused. You used LangChain's RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter for this.
3. Embedding generation — each chunk was passed through OpenAI's text-embedding-ada-002 model to produce a 1536-dimensional float vector.
4. Upsert to Pinecone — vectors were upserted in batches with metadata (drug name, source URL) so retrieved results are traceable back to their source.
5. At query time — a patient transcript vector queries the index using cosine similarity. Top-k results (k=5) are returned and injected into the GPT-4 prompt as context.

GCP Deployment

Docker - Containerizing the Streamlit app
I wrote a Dockerfile that packages the Streamlit app, its Python dependencies, and environment config into a portable container. This ensures the app runs identically on your local machine and on GCP.
FROM python:3.10-slim
WORKDIR /app
COPY requirements.txt .
RUN pip install -r requirements.txt
COPY . .
EXPOSE 8501
CMD ["streamlit", "run", "main.py", "--server.port=8501"]

GCP - Deployment on Google Compute Engine
1. GCE VM provisioned — you spun up a Linux VM on Google Compute Engine (e2-medium or similar), which gives a persistent public IP address.
2. Docker installed on VM — SSH'd in, installed Docker, pulled the image or built it directly on the instance.
3. Firewall rule added — opened port 8501 in GCP's VPC firewall so the app is reachable at the public IP.
4. App runs at static IP — the live URL was http://35.227.43.169:8501/. Docker was run with --restart=always so it auto-recovers if the container crashes.
5. Secrets managed — API keys (OpenAI, Pinecone, Firebase) were injected as environment variables via docker run -e flags or a .env file, never hardcoded in source.

docker-compose - Multi-service orchestration
The repo has a docker-compose.yml — this lets me define the Streamlit service, environment variables, and port mappings in one file and start everything with docker-compose up.
AI Models

OpenAI is the company that provides AI models as a service via API. Think of it as the vendor.
GPT-4 is a specific model made by OpenAI — it's the large language model that actually reads text and generates intelligent responses. In Perclias, GPT-4 is the brain that reads the patient transcript + retrieved medication context and writes the clinical summary.
Whisper is also an OpenAI model, but a completely different one — it's specialized for audio-to-text transcription, not text generation. So OpenAI gives you two models here: Whisper for ears, GPT-4 for reasoning.
LangChain is not an AI model at all. It's an open-source Python framework that helps you orchestrate and connect AI models into pipelines. It doesn't think or generate anything on its own — it's the plumbing.

In Perclias specifically, the division of labor is:
Whisper → converts doctor-patient audio into text
LangChain → takes that text, queries Pinecone for relevant medication context, assembles the prompt with that context, and calls GPT-4
GPT-4 → reads the assembled prompt and generates the clinical summary
